<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   50th Session of UN Human Rights Commission Opens </TI></H3>
<H4>   'Arafat on `Abuses' in Territories </H4>
<F P=102> LD0102133794 Bern Swiss Radio International in English 1100 
GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0102133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern Swiss Radio International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Palestine Liberation Organization leader, Yasir 
'Arafat, says he hopes to sign an agreement next week on a first 
Israeli troop withdrawal from the occupied territories. Mr. 
'Arafat told the United Nations Human Rights Commission in 
Geneva that he would hold further talks with the Israeli foreign 
minister, Shim'on Peres, in the Egyptian capital, Cairo. 
However, Israel has played down hopes of a final agreement on 
implementing Palestinian self-rule. The Israeli prime minister, 
Yitzhaq Rabin, said time was needed to overcome differences, 
while one official said an accord could be weeks away. 
  Mr. 'Arafat said on Monday [31 January] that a total 
agreement had been reached at talks in the Swiss resort of 
Davos, but that Mr. Peres asked for more time to study details 
of the text. In his speech to the Human Rights Commission he 
said the Palestinians were still suffering abuses in the 
occupied territories. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

