<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   50th Session of UN Human Rights Commission Opens </TI></H3>
<H4>   India Replies to Bhutto Charges </H4>
<F P=102> BK0202102394 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0202102394 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The former chief minister of Jammu and Kashmir, Dr. 
Farooq Abdullah, has dismissed Pakistan's accusations of 
widespread human rights violations in India. Exercising India's 
right to reply to the Pakistan prime minister, Ms. Benazir 
Bhutto's, statement on Kashmir, Dr. Abdullah reminded Islamabad 
of the plight of the Ahmediyas, the Shi'ites and other minority 
communities in Pakistan. Addressing the opening session of the 
Human Rights Commission in Geneva, he observed that India always 
stood by its pledge and commitment of giving equal rights to all 
citizens. Dr. Abdullah asserted that Kashmir was and will 
remain a part of India. 
  In a BBC interview later, he accused Pakistan of fomenting 
insurgency in Kashmir. He said India wants peace, but Pakistan 
is not responding to the offer. 

</TEXT>

