<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arab, Israeli Delegates Continue Washington Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   'Arafat Said To Favor Confederation </H4>
<F P=102> TA0102160594 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 1400 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA0102160594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres will meet U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher in a few hours to update 
him on the progress made in the Davos talks. Meanwhile, the 
bilateral talks between the Israeli, Syrian, Lebanese, and 
Palestinian delegations continue in Washington. Our 
correspondent Natan Gutman reports from Washington: 
  [Begin recording] [Gutman] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres 
arrived at his Washington hotel a short time ago. From what he 
told us, it appears that Mr. Peres is slightly less optimistic 
than Yasir 'Arafat concerning the chances of signing an 
agreement next week. I asked Shim'on Peres whether he shares 
'Arafat's assessment that an agreement can be signed within a 
week: 
  [Peres] I am participating in the negotiations, and that is 
enough for me. I hope we will reach an agreement, but I do not 
want to commit myself to a precise day or week. 
  [Gutman] What will take place in Cairo next week? 
  [Peres] We have to finalize several more issues, some of 
which relate to the contents of the agreement, others to the 
formulation of the issues on which agreement has been reached. 
  [Gutman] Upon his arrival in Washington, Foreign Minister 
Peres confirmed that Yasir 'Arafat told him in Davos that the 
Palestinians are not interested in an independent Palestinian 
state at the present time. 'Arafat told Peres at the opening of 
their meeting: You are afraid we want to establish a 
Palestinian state right now, but in fact we have decided to 
proceed toward a confederation rather than a Palestinian state. 
This is what 'Arafat told Peres at the opening of their meeting 
in Davos. 
  Foreign Minister Peres will meet Secretary of State 
Christopher in about three hours, and tomorrow he will meet Vice 
President Gore. The talks between the Israeli and Syrian 
delegations will open in about half an hour -- a breakthrough on 
this track is not expected to take place today. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

