<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abu-Shawarib To Go to Amman for Signing Ceremony </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0102131294 Amman AL-DUSTUR in Arabic 1 Feb 94 p 30 </F>
<F P=103> JN0102131294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-DUSTUR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Salih al-Qallab] </F>
  [Excerpt] Sanaa -- Brigadier General Mujahid Abu-Shawarib, 
the Yemeni deputy prime minister and chairman of the committee 
preparing for a reconciliation session between President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih and his deputy 'Ali Salim al-Bid, has announced 
that, barring unforeseen difficulties, he will travel to Amman 
next Thursday to prepare for the signing of the document of 
understanding initialed by leaders of the country's parties and 
independent figures in Aden 18 January. 
  Mujahid Abu-Shawarib, a key figure in the national dialogue 
that spawned the document of understanding to be signed by the 
Yemeni president and his deputy in Amman next week, indicated 
that agreement has been reached as to which local, Arab, and 
other parties will be invited to attend the signing ceremonies. 
  Since the accord was initialed, the General People's 
Congress 
[GPC] and the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP] have differed over 
which Arab and other states to invite for the event. 
  While the YSP wants Britain, France, the United States, 
Eritrea, Canada, and China to be present along with Oman, Saudi 
Arabia, Syria, Egypt, and the Arab League, the GPC prefers a 
restricted attendance. 
  Abu-Shawarib said that agreement has been reached to invite 
five Yemeni figures from the three ruling coalition partners: 
the GPC, the YSP, and the Reform Party, a representative from 
each of the parties that sat on the dialogue committee, 
including the Arab Socialist Ba'th Party, al-Haqq Party, and the 
Yemeni Reform Grouping, plus a limited number of independents. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

