<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties Said Preparing for Separation, Military Clash </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0102211494 Cairo AL-AHRAM in Arabic 29 Jan 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> NC0102211494 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-AHRAM </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Kamal Jaballah in Sanaa] </F>
  [Text] A ranking Yemeni Government official has announced 
that the General People's Congress [GPC] set the return of 'Ali 
Salim al-Bid, vice president and secretary general of the Yemeni 
Socialist Party [YSP], and Prime Minister Haydar Abu-Bakr 
al-'Attas to Sanaa to assume their duties as a condition for 
signing the "Pledge and Accord" document outside Yemen. 
  The official, who asked not to be identified, said that if 
the document is not signed before the month of Ramadan 
[approximately 10 February] it will mean that the YSP is buying 
more time to prepare for separation. In his statement to 
AL-AHRAM, the official expected a violent military confrontation 
between the two sides if the crisis is not resolved. He noted 
that YSP media are now paving the way for separation. 
  The official's statement coincided with growing speculation 
by politicians and observers in Sanaa that the antagonist 
political forces are preparing to divide Yemen once again into 
two parts and perhaps more, as Hadhramaut is expected to secede 
from the southern part. Informed Yemeni sources that asked to 
remain anonymous said separation is now a matter of time and of 
who will bear the responsibility before history and the Yemeni 
people. 
  The sources said: The two poles of government, the GPC and 
the YSP, are accusing each other not only of escalating the 
crisis but of actually preparing for military confrontation if 
separation intentions come true. 
  The sources said that before inaugurating the Hadhramaut oil 
project, the YSP raised the cost of the project by $300 million 
without the Council of Ministers or the Presidential Council 
knowing about it. The additional money, according to the 
sources, was used to buy weapons and ammunition in preparation 
for the possible confrontation. For its part, the YSP accused 
the GPC of buying some $20 million worth of weapons and 
ammunition from Romania without the knowledge of the prime 
minister, who belongs to the YSP. 

</TEXT>

