<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Officials Said To Support Davos Document </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0202120094 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 2 Feb 94 p A2 </F>
<F P=103> TA0202120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Aluf Ben] </F>
  [Excerpt] Senior defense sources, headed by Chief of Staff 
Ehud Baraq, told Yitzhaq Rabin, prime minister and defense 
minister, that although they have "minor and marginal" 
observations about the document of understandings worked out 
Sunday [30 January] in Davos, they will support the document if 
PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat signs it, senior political sources in 
Jerusalem said yesterday. 
  The sources said that "if 'Arafat would have signed the 
document first, Rabin would have accepted it." The sources said 
that during the Davos meeting, there was ongoing telephone and 
facsimile contacts between Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres and 
the prime minister, as well as between Major General 'Uzi Dayan, 
a member of the Israeli delegation, and the military top brass. 
  Ongoing consultations were also held between Rabin, Baraq, 
Deputy Chief of Staff Amnon Shahaq, head of intelligence Uri 
Sagi, and the Shin Bet chief. They transmitted their comments 
to Davos by facsimile. "The Army top brass had many 
observations about the initial drafts presented to the 
Palestinian delegation," the political sources said, "but they 
support the final document. They said that they have comments 
on several minor and noncritical points, but in principle they 
feel that the PLO accepted the Israeli position." 
  In deliberations held prior to the foreign minister's 
departure for Davos, in which the prime minister and the defense 
team participated, the Army brass firmly opposed for security 
reasons some of the proposals raised by Peres. They demanded 
that Israel keep full control of the roads to the Gaza Strip 
settlements and that it be made clear that the IDF [Israel 
Defense Forces] will continue to move along the traffic axes 
termed "safe corridors" between Jericho and the Allenby Bridge, 
al-Nabi Musa, and the Dead Sea. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

