<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shahal Opens Civil Guard Station in Territories </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA3101115694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 1100 GMT 31 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA3101115694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Police Minister Moshe Shahal this morning opened 
a Civil Guard station at Ma'ale Adumim, the first in the 
territories. Speaking at the opening ceremony, he promised that 
the Civil Guard units will be limited to patrolling within the 
settlement itself. The police minister also said that five other 
Civil Guard stations will be opened shortly in the territories. 
Reporter Mark Weiss asked Minister Shahal about the 
significance of the opening: 
  [Begin recording] [Shahal] A decision has been taken about 
a year ago, and the previous government decided to implement the 
idea of having this guard, like in any other parts in Israel. I 
think that the significance is that we are looking upon Ma'ale 
Adumim as any other town, and we rely on the citizens of this 
town to be responsible for their security, to help the police 
force. I think this is the political significance of the 
decision. 
  [Weiss] Do you believe this new Civil Guard will be able to 
cooperate with the Palestinian police force to be set up under 
autonomy? 
  [Shahal] Well, I think that there will be a need of 
cooperation. If the Palestinian police force cares for the 
security, to deal with and to prevent crime, I think that it 
will be necessary to cooperate on all levels, and we hope that 
this is going to happen. Any professional police force need 
this kind of cooperation. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

