<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Criticizes Clinton Policy on Sanctions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0102185594 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1700 GMT 1 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0102185594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Baghdad, Sa'd Qasim Hammudi, secretary general of 
the Arab Popular Forces Conference, has accused U.S. President 
Clinton of seeking to extend the anti-Iraq embargo and 
criticized his conditions for reducing international sanctions. 
Hammudi, who is also a member of the Iraqi Ba'th Party's 
Foreign Relations Committee, described Clinton's message as one 
of blackmail. 
  This is the first Iraqi official reaction to Clinton's 
message to Congress in which he expressed his fears that the 
Iraqi authorities might rebuild Iraq's mass destruction arsenal. 
Clinton demanded a long period of monitoring on Iraq's military 
establishments before any reduction of the sanctions is effected. 

</TEXT>

