<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Forces Kill 43 `Rebel Troops' in Kabul </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0102171394 Hong Kong AFP in English 1648 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0102171394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Islamabad, Feb 1 (AFP) -- Troops loyal to Afghan 
President Borhanoddin Rabbani killed 43 rebel troops and wounded 
another 300 in clashes in Kabul Tuesday, the state-run Radio 
Kabul said in a broadcast monitored here. 
  The militia of Hezb-i-Islami leader Prime Minister Golboddin 
Hekmatyar suffered 43 dead and 50 injured after attacking state 
forces and being repulsed, the radio said. 
  In another engagement with the Uzbek militia of General 
Abdul 
Rashid Dostam, allied with Hekmatyar, the pro-Rabbani forces 
wounded 300 rebels in the Microrayan area of Kabul, the 
broadcast said. 
  The radio said the Dostam militia has lost 1,000 men during 
the month-long fighting, which erupted when the Uzbek warlord 
launched an offensive on January 1, in cooperation with the 
Hezb, to oust Rabbani from power. 
  Meanwhile, Afghan sources in the Pakistani border city of 
Peshawar said a 100-member mission comprising mojhedin 
commanders, religious scholars and elders had launched a new 
initiative to end the bloodshed. 
  The mediation team, led by commander Jalaluddin Haqqani, 
left 
the eastern Afghan city of Jalalabad Tuesday for Kabul for talks 
with the warring sides. 
  Last month, more than 40 commanders from the Kabul area made 
two attempts to bring about a ceasefire, but failed to bring 
Rabbani and Hekmatyar to the negotiating table. 

</TEXT>

