<H3> <TI>   Nine Arab Youths Killed in Fighting Near Kabul </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0102143394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1210 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0102143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kabul, 1 Feb (MENA)--Nine Arab youths were killed 
during the fighting that raged yesterday southwest of the Afghan 
capital Kabul, during which forces loyal to Afghan President 
Borhanoddin Rabbani seized one of the positions controlled by 
Prime Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar in the (?Jowzjan) area. 
  Mohammad Yunus Kanuni, the political counselor at the Afghan 
Defense Ministry, told MENA that these youths' identities have 
not been ascertained yet but interrogation of other prisoners 
showed that they were Egyptian, Sudanese, and Algerian nationals. 
  He regretted the fact that the names of those killed are not 
known so as to inform their families. He said that Hekmatyar's 
forces took away their passports as soon as they joined and gave 
them aliases that do not indicate their real identities. 
  In reply to a question on how these youths had come to the 
areas of fighting in Afghanistan, Yunus said that a number of 
service offices that operate under false Islamic names succeeded 
in enticing these youths to come to Afghanistan under the false 
pretext of "Islamic jihad." 
  The Afghan official expressed hope that Muslim youths will 
understand what the real situation in Afghanistan is before they 
think of traveling to it under false slogans that take jihad as 
their symbol. He added that the service offices treat these 
groups as mercenaries. 

</TEXT>

