<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks With China for Submarine Purchases `Put Off' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2801112594 Islamabad THE NEWS in English 28 Jan 94 p 12 </F>
<F P=103> BK2801112594 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad THE NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Islamabad -- The arrival of Chinese team for 
negotiations with Pakistani officials and experts for the sale 
of three S-20, diesel-electric powered submarines, has been put 
off for two weeks. 
  The Chinese team, which will also include officials of the 
China State Shipbuilding Corporation (CSSC) -- the manufacturer 
of S-20 submarine -- was earlier scheduled to arrive here by 
January 31 for detailed negotiations on the possibility of 
selling out three units of S-20 to Pakistan. 
  Official sources told `The News' on Thursday: "Now the 
Chinese team will reach here towards the end of first half of 
February." 
  The CSSC is offering its on-trial newly-designed S-20 
submarines to Pakistan. The cost of three units will be nearly 
540 million US dollars. 
  Meanwhile, week-long talks with Swedish team for T-96 have 
already been completed and detailed negotiations with the 
visiting French team are currently under way for Agosta 90B 
submarine which is an ungraded but non-nuclear version of Agosta 
being manufactured by DCN-I of France. 
  Official sources confirmed that talks for the purchase of 
submarines are being held only with three countries, France, 
Sweden and China. These sources say that "though possibility of 
negotiations with any other country cannot be totally ruled out, 
at present Pakistan has not invited any other country, except 
these three, for negotiations on the particular subject." 
  Defence sources told 'The News' that Pakistan wants to sign 
the contract for the purchase of three submarines as early as 
possible once the on-going process of pre-contract negotiations 
with these three countries are completed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

