<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arms Control, Regional Security Committee Meets </TI></H3>
<H4>   Palestinian Official Comments </H4>
<F P=102> NC0302103594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0830 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0302103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 3 Feb (MENA)--Ziyad Abu-Zayyad, head of the 
Palestinian delegation to the meetings of the committee on arms 
control and regional security stemming from the multilateral 
talks, has stated that the Palestinian party is still opposed to 
and has reservations on the proposed joint paper that is being 
discussed by the subcommittee because it contains certain 
political issues that should not be discussed by the arms 
control committee. In a statement to MENA today on the 
sidelines of the committee meeting, he said that the paper still 
contains numerous political items that are the jurisdiction of 
the bilateral negotiations, which are considered to be the basis 
of the political process. He noted that the paper that will be 
adopted at the conclusion of the meetings in Cairo will not be 
"a recommendation" but a "draft" that will be submitted to the 
Arab countries to give their official view. It will then be put 
forward to the general arms control committee meeting scheduled 
for April. 
  Meanwhile, an official source in the United Arab Emirates 
delegation participating in the meetings of the arms control and 
regional security committee said that the United States and 
Russia, in their capacity as cosponsors of the peace conference 
should endorse on any joint principles adopted by the current 
meetings in Cairo and not just take a neutral stand. In a 
statement to MENA, he said that his country insists on the two 
cosponsors' approval and endorsement of any formula on 
principles reached by the Middle East countries so that both 
countries will be committed to that formula in the future. He 
said that this point is still under discussion because both 
cosponsors favor a neutral stance on the position the conferees 
intend to adopt. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

