<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Sources' Report Efforts To Build Airport in Sinai </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0202144694 Jerusalem AL-NAHAR in Arabic 2 Feb 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> TA0202144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem AL-NAHAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By 'Abd-al-Ra'uf Arna'ut] </F>
  [Text] Jerusalem -- Informed Palestinian sources have said 
that Palestinian-Egyptian talks were held recently on the 
possibility of leasing a piece of land parallel to al-'Arish 
region on the Egyptian borders with the Gaza Strip to the 
Palestinian authority slated to be set up in accordance with the 
self-rule agreement. 
  Those sources added that the Palestinians sought to lease a 
40 square km area parallel to Rafah region, south of the Gaza 
Strip, on which to build an airport. This land extends from 
Rafah's boundaries to the village of Zuwayd in al-'Arish. 
  Palestinian experts estimate that at least 30 square km, 17 
square km of which will be used as runways, are required for the 
construction of this airport. 
  The Palestinian sources, who asked to remain anonymous, said 
that the reason the Palestinians approached Egypt and asked to 
lease this land was "because of lack of space in the Gaza Strip, 
which is suffering from an immense population density." 
  Some 800,000 Palestinians live in the Gaza Strip, which is a 
360 square km area, 80 square km of which have been confiscated 
by Israel for building settlements. According to these sources, 
negotiations over the Palestinian request have so far failed to 
yield any results. 

</TEXT>

