<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Comments on Raid of `Terrorist' Hideout </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0202170694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1410 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0202170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 2 Feb (MENA)--Interior Minister Hasan al-Alfi 
announced today that the terrorists killed in a hideout in 
northern Cairo's al-Zawiyah al-Hamra' neighborhood yesterday 
were prominent and dangerous terrorists known for their recent 
violent acts in Upper Egypt. 
  He added that the group included several suspects who had 
been on the run and others who had been convicted in connection 
with numerous terrorist cases in Upper Egypt. He said that in 
yesterday's incident no escapes occurred. 
  The interior minister explained that information was 
received 
that a group of fugitive terrorists were staying in a hideout in 
al- Zawiyah al-Hamra' and that after obtaining permission from 
the Prosecutor's Office, the hideout was stormed. He added that 
the terrorists opened fire on the security forces, who returned 
the fire. He said that a detailed statement will be issued 
later today naming the suspects and the details of the incident. 
  Al-Alfi continued that a quantity of bombs, ammunition, 
explosives, and weapons that the terrorists had been using in 
their operations were discovered in the hideout. He pointed out 
that the security forces found large sums of money with the 
seven terrorists who were killed, proving that they were hired 
agents paid for their acts, which he termed cowardly and vile. 
  The interior minister said that the police will not rest as 
long as one terrorist remains at large in Egypt but will pursue 
and arrest him. 
  The interior minister reaffirmed that the police have the 
initiative now and are conducting campaigns of arrests and 
surveillance against terrorists and all those linked to violent 
and terrorist crimes. He explained that the police are using 
scientific methods and careful planning that are based on full 
information. 
  Asked if Egypt has signed a security cooperation agreement 
with Pakistan to extradite fugitive terrorists, the interior 
minister said that there are agreements and contacts with 
various countries to exchange data and extradite criminals. 
  Hasan al-Alfi, who was speaking after inspecting an 
exhibition of stolen goods organized by the Cairo Security 
Directorate, concluded his remarks by saying that public 
security is one integral whole and that it operates concurrently 
on security, economic, criminal, and social levels. He 
explained that the police are making great efforts in all these 
fields based on the concept that their work is a vocation and 
not a mere job. 
  [Cairo MENA in Arabic at 1336 GMT on 2 February carries a 
related report about the al-Zawiyah al-Hamra' police raid, 
saying: "Counselor 'Abd-al-Sami' Sharaf al-Din, public attorney 
for the Higher State Security Department, has ordered autopsies 
on the bodies of seven terrorists killed yesterday to determine 
the cause of death. The Prosecutor's Office ordered forensic 
officials to inspect the site of the incident, prepare a report, 
and submit it to the prosecution. 
  ["Counselor 'Abd-al-Sami' Sharaf al-Din inspected the 
terrorists' hideout and impounded three automatic weapons, 12 
bombs, three remote control devices, large quantities of TNT, 
and a police radio that the terrorists had stolen from an 
officer at Abu Tij Police Station after killing him. Later 
today prosecutors will question eyewitnesses and the police 
officers who took part in the raid."] 

</TEXT>

