<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   JANA Chides France for Actions in Algeria </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202160594 Tripoli JANA in English 1439 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202160594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli JANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tripoli, al-Nowar [February] 2, JAMAHIRIYAH NEWS 
AGENCY -- The assistant official spokeswoman for the French 
Foreign Ministry Catherine Colonna said that France hopes that 
the new Algerian president, Liamine Zeroual, will carry out a 
genuine political dialogue with all Algerian parties. This will 
serve to place Algeria on the road to democracy and national 
reconciliation. 
  The JAMAHIRIYAH NEWS AGENCY's Arab affairs editor commented 
on this saying: 
  These official French statements constitute a blatant 
interference in the internal affairs of friendly Algeria. At 
the same time, France has acted in a silly manner towards 
Algeria. The editor added that if France had, for example, 
called for building cordial relations with Algeria then this 
would be reasonable. However, for officials to meddle in an 
internal matter which concerns Algeria, as was the case with the 
statements made by the French spokeswoman, then the matter is 
both silly and constitutes a blatant interference in Algeria's 
internal affairs. 
  The editor said that if no one could be found to say this 
then the Great Jamahiriyah will say it [word indistinct] in a 
loud voice, for France continues to see itself as a colonial 
power and as if it is its mentor. It is as if Algeria belongs 
to France and Algeria sacrificed one million and a half martyrs 
in the battles for independence and freedom against French 
colonialism. 
  Such interference, propelled by a colonialist bias, can only 
serve to increase the anger we feel against France, its 
`colonial master' mentality, and the spirit of a colonialist 
country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

