<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Country's Nationality, Citizenship Law Examined </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0202133694 Beirut AL-SHIRA' in Arabic 31 Jan 94 pp 16, 17 </F>
<F P=103> NC0202133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut AL-SHIRA' </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [All Sudanese placenames as published] </F>
  [Text] Some Arab and Western capitals are following with 
great interest the trend within the Sudanese Government to grant 
Sudanese citizenship to any Muslim, since this is considered a 
first of its kind by a government since the naturalization law 
was created. 
  Diplomatic sources in Cairo noted that the Khartoum 
government intends to pass a new draft law on naturalization. 
This law stipulates granting Sudanese citizenship to every 
Muslim this coming month. The sources added that if this 
happens, large numbers of extremist terrorists will find shelter 
and a land to use as a springboard for their terrorist 
activities. 
  It is worth noting here that the current naturalization law 
stipulates that the applicant for citizenship must have resided 
in Sudan for not less than 12 years and should not have a 
criminal record of a crime that violates security and honor. 
  These diplomatic sources noted that there are more than 
5,000 
men and women extremist Muslims residing in Sudan. Most of them 
are from Algeria, Tunisia, Egypt, Saudi Arabia, and Palestine. 
The number of Islamists from Morocco known to these sources is 
50. There are over 370 Egyptians known by their "code" 
[preceding word in English] names. There are also over 300 
Tunisians who belong to the Ennahda Movement headed by Rachid 
Ghanouchi. 
  These sources noted that among these groups, there are some 
Syrians, Iraqis, and Yemenis who live in Sudan under the cover 
of being businessmen and contractors. Most of these Islamists 
live in the areas of al-Riyad, al-Ta'if, al-Manshiyah, Kawbar, 
and Madinat al-Mughtaribin in Madinat al-Khartoum Bahri. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

