<H3> <TI>   Beilin: Tourists Can Visit Egypt Despite Threats </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0302115894 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 1100 GMT 3 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0302115894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi Beilin says Israel is 
counting on Egyptian authorities to deal with violence by 
militants in that country, and that Jerusalem is not 
recommending that Israelis stay out of Egypt. Egyptian 
militants have warned foreigners to leave the country for their 
own safety, saying the next attacks will be extremely ferocious 
and strong. Deputy Foreign Minister Beilin gave the Israeli 
assessment to reporter Jack Katzenell: 
  [Begin recording] [Beilin] Well, we are of course following 
the situation, but we are sure that the Egyptian Government is 
able to handle this situation and to take care of those 
developments which are, of course, not very positive, but still 
are far from representing the general mood in Egypt. 
  [Katzenell] Do you think that Israelis can still visit 
Egypt, or should still visit Egypt as tourists? 
  [Beilin] We are not calling on Israelis not to visit Egypt. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

