<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin, Tzomet Leader React </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0202193994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 1800 GMT 2 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0202193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tzomet leader Refa'el Eytan says he has given the 
party's internal ombudsman the go-ahead to use outside advisers 
to help investigate claims of financial irregularities and 
mismanagement of party affairs. Speaking at a press conference, 
Eytan described Gonen Segev, Ester Salmovitz, and Alex 
Goldfarb's breakaway as an attempt to strengthen their positions 
in the upcoming elections. Eytan said he was not surprised by 
reports of their possible plans to join the coalition. 
  Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin says the Labor party must not 
get involved in the internal political problems of the Tzomet 
party. Speaking to reporters tonight in Jerusalem, Rabin refused 
to say whether he would attempt to entice the three resigning 
members to join the coalition and, in his words, would not 
answer hypothetical questions. 
  [Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network in Hebrew at 
1800 GMT on 2 February adds that Rabin "stated a short time ago 
that he had not authorized anybody to negotiate with the three 
seceding members of Tzomet."] 

</TEXT>

