<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   IDF Policy on Settlers' Demonstrations Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0302053594 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0302053594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The settlers' operation aimed at doubling the 
number of existing settlements continued this evening. Dozens 
of settlers set up a new outpost near the settlement of Yaqir on 
the trans-Samaria highway. [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 
1900 GMT on 2 February reports that "the 50 settlers from Yaqir 
who attempted to set up a new settlement on a hill next to their 
settlement left the site after the Army declared the area a 
closed military zone. Our correspondent Dani Gur-Arye reports 
that no confrontation occurred between the soldiers and the 
settlers."] 
  IDF [Israel Defense Forces] officers said that the operation 
impedes the routine activities of the IDF, which is compelled to 
assign a large number of troops to evacuate the settlers. The 
organizers of the operation, called This Is Our Land, say that 
the operation will continue in all 130 settlements, or until 
50,000 people are arrested. As is known, the leaders of the 
Council of Jewish Settlements in Judaea, Samaria, and Gaza 
object to the operation, but have nevertheless announced they 
will provide legal assistance to settlers who are arrested. 
[passage omitted] 
  The struggle between the official leadership of the settlers 
and activists in the field in fact exists only on paper. This 
week, an attempt will be made to close ranks in anticipation of 
the deployment of Israel Police in the territories in place of 
the IDF. [passage omitted] 
  The IDF announced today that demonstrations by Jews in the 
territories will henceforth be allowed only within the Jewish 
settlements, just as demonstrations by Arabs will be allowed 
only within Arab locations. Our legal affairs correspondent 
Shlomo Arad reports that the High Court of Justice today 
rejected the settlers' request to demonstrate in the synagogue 
in Jericho based on this policy, arguing that the synagogue is 
located in an Arab location and that the court was convinced 
that such a move could imperil security on the site. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

