<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Settlers' Attempt To Squat in Arab Homes Thwarted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0202071894 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 0500 GMT 2 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0202071894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Samaria, security forces last night thwarted an 
attempt by Kfar Tapuah settlers to squat in Arab homes in the 
nearby village of Kafr Yusuf, as part of the shadow settlements 
group of the This Is Our Land operation. The area was declared 
a closed military zone and settlers were requested to leave. 
Eleven settlers who refused were taken into custody. A 
spokesman for the This Is Our Land condemned the actions of the 
Kfar Tapuah settlers and said his group's aim was to settle on 
state land, not to take over private Arab homes. 
  The committee of Jordan Valley settlements is planning to 
establish a special patrol unit to be known as the Jordan Valley 
Watch. It will carry out regular patrols in the Jordan Valley, 
including the territorial corridors due under the proposed 
autonomy accord to link Jericho to nearby Muslim and Christian 
holy sites and to the northern Dead Sea area. The spokesman for 
the committee told Qol Yisra'el that the patrols have a 
deterrent purpose and are aimed also to demonstrate an Israeli 
presence on the Jordan Valley roads. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-34052 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes023_l_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-023 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

