<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Judge, Jordanian Envoy Discuss Diplomat's Murder </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0202180594 Beirut Radio Lebanon in Arabic 1630 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0202180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Radio Lebanon </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Regarding the ongoing investigations into the crime 
[assassination of Jordanian diplomat], Beirut's first 
investigations Judge Sa'id Mirzah met with Jordanian Ambassador 
Fakhri Abu-Talib at the embassy at 1800 today to discuss the 
circumstances of the incident. The meeting was attended by a 
Jordanian delegation that accompanied the ambassador. The 
delegation includes Jordanian Foreign Ministry Counselor Hamzah 
'Abd-al-Qadir and a police colonel. A number of Lebanese 
security commanders also participated in the meeting. 
  President Ilyas al-Hirawi has sent Deputy Prime Minister 
Michel al-Murr to the Jordanian Embassy to offer condolences. 
Al-Murr conveyed to Ambassador Abu-Talib the condolences of the 
Lebanese Government and people. He noted that the president was 
eager to delegate him personally to show solidarity with the 
Jordanian king and people and with the embassy in particular. 
Ambassador Abu-Talib said the incident targeted Lebanon's 
security and stability. 
  Ambassador Abu-Talib returned from Amman today after 
accompanying the Jordanian diplomat's body there and received 
condolences at the embassy. 
  Minister of Labor 'Abdallah al-Amin cabled condolences to 
the 
Jordanian foreign minister, saying that the painful incident was 
a stab at Lebanon's security and peace. 

</TEXT>

