<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Factions Declare Jalalabad Safe Haven </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202141394 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service in 
English 1300 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0202141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Afghan warring factions have agreed to declare 
Jalalabad a safe haven, at the instance of Pakistan. A Foreign 
Office spokesman told newsmen in Islamabad today, that the 
agreement came after meetings separately of Pakistan's charge 
d'affaires in Kabul with President Borhanoddin Rabbani and Prime 
Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar. He said there has also been a 
positive response from General 'Abdorrahim [as heard] Dostam, 
when the acting consul general of Pakistan contacted him at 
Mazar-e Sharif. 
  The spokesman said Pakistan would continue to provide 
humanitarian relief to the displaced people at Jalalabad. He 
said Pakistan was pressing all parties to the conflict to accept 
a cease- fire. 
  On the other hand, the 100-member Jalalabad mediation team, 
which arrived in Pol-e Charkhi near Kabul last night, has 
started informal contacts with leaders of the warring factions, 
to prepare the groundwork for negotiations. 
  Meanwhile a rocket and heavy artillery exchange rocked the 
Afghan capital for more than an hour today. Forces opposing the 
government attacked Kabul's [word indistinct] Wazir Akbar Khan 
district with rockets. The pro-government batteries retaliated 
for more than an a hour. 

</TEXT>

