<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   4-Day Conditional Cease-fire Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202231594 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 2030 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0202231594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Afghan opposition coordination council 
announced: After a call by the United Nations, opposition forces 
have agreed to a four-day conditional cease-fire. This is when 
warring groups in Afghanistan have also agreed to set Jalalabad 
as a secure area. Here is our colleague, Khameneh, in Pakistan 
with a report: 
  [Khameneh] The leaders of the warring groups in Kabul have 
agreed to declare Jalalabad, in eastern Afghanistan, as a secure 
area where clashes and military operations will be avoided. 
  The Afghan President Borhanoddin Rabbani, and the Prime 
Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar, in separate meetings with the 
Pakistani Charge d'affaires in the last 48 hours, have shown a 
positive reaction to a call by Pakistan for declaring Jalalabad 
as a secure area. A spokesman for the Pakistani Ministry for 
Foreign Affairs, in a news conference this evening, announcing 
this, added: The acting Pakistani consul in Mazar-e Sharif, 
also, in a meeting with General Dostam has received a similar 
response to the call. 
  After recent clashes among rival groups in Kabul, which 
began 
33 days ago, about 80,000 out of 250,000 Afghan refugees have 
sought refuge in Jalalabad and its suburbs. Pakistan's efforts 
to declare Jalalabad as a secure area can be construed as a 
restraining act toward Afghan refugees entering Pakistani soil. 
During the first 10 days of fighting in Kabul, about 17,000 new 
Afghan refugees entered Pakistan and eventually, some three 
weeks ago, Islamabad banned Afghan nationals from entering that 
country without a valid visa. 

</TEXT>

