<F P=100> Bangladesh </F>
<H3> <TI>   Six Killed, 30 Injured in Attack on Opposition Parade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK3101162894 Hong Kong AFP in English 0956 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK3101162894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dhaka, Jan 31 (AFP) -- At least six people were 
killed and 30 others injured Monday when an opposition Awami 
League (AL) procession was fired on by unidentified gunmen, 
pushing the toll to seven in election violence, police and 
witnesses said. 
  Gunmen opened fire on the supporters of AL mayoral candidate 
Mohammad Hanif, who is leading in the weekend polls, in the 
Lalbagh area, killing six instantly. Several of the injured were 
in critical condition. 
  "We do not have any details on who fired," one police 
officer 
at the Lalbagh police station said. 
  The injured were being treated at a local hospital. 
  During Sunday's first ever mayoral and city commissioner 
elections, one school boy was killed and more than 200 were 
injured in sporadic clashes between rival groups. 
  Hanif is leading with a wide margin against Prime Minister 
Khaleda Zia's ruling Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) nominee 
Mirza Abbas in Dhaka, while another AL candidate, Mohiuddin 
Chowdhury, has won in the port city of Chittagong, according to 
preliminary election commission results. 
  But the BNP clinched victory in the cities of Khulna and 
Rajshahi. 
  The elections are seen here as the first popularity test of 
the two main political groups, and political analysts said the 
AL sees the municipal vote as a way of rebuilding its strength 
in crucial urban areas before the 1996 national polls, after 
losing all eight Dhaka seats and most of the other urban seats 
to the BNP in the 1991 parliamentary election. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

