<H3> <TI>   Other Relations Analyzed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0202192394 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran in 
Arabic 1730 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0202192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Station commentary] </F>
  [Excerpts] [Passage omitted] Egyptian President Husni 
Mubarak and the accompanying delegation returned to Cairo from 
Ankara last night following talks with his Turkish counterpart 
and other officials. [passage omitted] 
  The Egyptian president's lightning visit to Turkey was his 
third since 1985. Yesterday's meeting between Mubarak and his 
Turkish counterpart reveals the nature of relations between 
Cairo and Ankara. The meeting was aimed at expanding the scope 
of political, economic, cultural, and military cooperation 
between the two countries. This cooperation is of special 
importance in light of the two countries' status in the region 
and of their relations with Israel. 
  The Zionist entity's President Ezer Weizman paid an official 
four-day visit to Turkey one week before Mubarak's visit. 
Weizman said that the Middle East's future is dependent on 
cooperation between Israel, Turkey, and Egypt. A number of 
political observers believe that such meetings are a preparatory 
step toward concluding a regional alliance that will give the 
Egyptian, Israeli, and Turkish Governments the right opportunity 
for confronting every possible danger and for implementing their 
own policies. The United States is supporting this step to 
strengthen the ties of tripartite coordination and cooperation. 
The spread of the Islamic trend and the Islamic forces' 
activities topped the items discussed by Turkey, Israel, and 
Egypt. 
  On the other hand, it can be said that strengthening Turkish 
and Egyptian relations with the Zionist entity prepares the 
proper ground for the normalization of relations between the 
other Arab countries and the usurper entity. It also prepares 
the ground for lifting the Arab economic boycott of this entity. 
This is quite evident to anyone who analyzes the political 
trend. 
  The Islamic trend in the region is the primary target of the 
policy of developing relations between Egypt, Israel, and 
Turkey. This policy aims to tighten the noose around the 
countries that exercise independent policies that are not linked 
to the imperialist forces. 

</TEXT>

