<H3> <TI>   Azeri Official on `Western Meddlings' in Azerbaijan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101213194 Tehran IRNA in English 1848 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3101213194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, Jan. 31, IRNA -- Head of Azeri Parliamentary 
Delegation, Sultan Mohammadov said today that Western meddlings 
and Russian support for the current "unpleasant" situation in 
Azerbaijan are two threatening factors for the republic's 
independence. 
  In a meeting with Deputy Majlis Speaker, Hojjat ol-Eslam Dr. 
Hasan Rowhani, he criticized international forums for keeping 
silent towards the five year-old Armenian aggression against the 
republic and accused them of adopting impractical measures. 
  He described Iran's Majlis as a "democratic, free and 
independent parliament" and said Azerbaijan could well benefit 
from Iran's experiences in the legislative field. 
  He appreciated Iran's assistance to the peoples of 
Azerbaijan 
and Nakhichevan and hoped for expansion of mutual relations in 
all areas. 
  Rowhani said that Iran condemns any aggression against the 
Azerbaijan Republic and believes that any change of borders will 
put regional security and stability in jeopardy. 
  Iran believes that military confrontations cannot bring any 
permanent settlement to the Karabakh conflict and that the 
dispute should be resolved through political and peaceful means, 
he added. 
  Rowhani stressed that Iran and Azerbaijan should promote 
bilateral cooperation especially in the economic, parliamentary, 
scientific and cultural fields. 
  He also expressed Iran's readiness to participate in 
economic 
projects in Azerbaijan especially in agriculture, industry, oil 
and joint operation in the Caspian Sea. 

</TEXT>

