<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin: No Accord Implementing Before Written Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0202161594 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1300 GMT 2 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0202161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin said today that 
Israel will not start implementing the Gaza-Jericho agreement 
before a written, mutually-acceptable, and detailed agreement 
has been attained. The prime minister added that only a miracle 
will enable the completion of the negotiations next week, and 
that some of the issues discussed in Davos remain open. The 
Palestinians have not reported to the economic talks in Paris 
for two weeks, Rabin stated, and the negotiations on the 
transfer of civil powers are stuck. Our political correspondent 
Shlomo Raz points out that the prime minister made these remarks 
after the signing ceremony of scientific agreements with Austria. 
  [Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew at 1400 GMT on 2 February 
adds: 
"Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin stated today that PLO leader Yasir 
'Arafat's goal is to establish a Palestinian state in the first 
stage, and a confederation with Jordan at a later stage." In a 
recorded passage in English, Rabin says: "To the best of my 
knowledge, the goal is a Palestinian state; perhaps after that a 
confederation. But, this is not my problem."] 
  [Referring to the reported criticism of security officials 
at 
the understandings reached in Davos by Foreign Minister Shim'on 
Peres and 'Arafat, Rabin said "he did not want to get into 
abstract and fabricated arguments."] 

</TEXT>

