<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   YSP Reportedly Seizes Missiles Sent to South </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0302204594 Amman Jordan Television Network in English 2000 
GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0302204594 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In a sign of complications in Yemen's political 
crisis, the Yemen Socialist Party said it seized antiaircraft 
missiles being moved by its northern rivals toward the south. A 
party spokesman said: An Army vehicle carrying 40 antiaircraft 
missiles from the north and heading south was seized by a 
southern brigade. He did not say when the missiles were seized, 
but said this was a new proof of the escalation of the political 
and the military tension in the country. 
  The announcement came hours after Planning Minister 
'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani blamed Vice President 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid's party for delaying the signing of an accord to end the 
political crisis paralyzing the country. Al-Iryani said: There 
are no arrangements for the signing of the accord neither in 
Amman nor inside Yemen as new conditions have been set by the 
Yemen Socialist Party. He said: The YSP wanted constitutional 
legal and security conditions not included in the accord. He 
did not give details, but political sources said the YSP was 
apparently seeking guarantees for its officials from security 
services run by the president's supporters. 

</TEXT>

