<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   GPC Claims South Massing Troops Against North </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0402082494 Paris AFP in English 0624 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0402082494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, Feb 4 (AFP) -- Southern Yemeni forces are 
massing along the former border between North and South Yemen, 
the northern-based General People's Congress (GPC) of President 
'Ali 'Abdallah Salih charged Thursday [3 February]. 
  "Dozens of tanks, troop transporters and missiles are 
concentrated in the Shabwah region," a congress spokesman told 
the press here. 
  Military units based in the north have not moved any of 
their 
missiles, he insisted, despite allegations to the contrary from 
the Yemeni Socialist Party (YSP), which operates in the south 
and whose leader, Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bid, is in 
conflict with Salih. 
  The YSP said that southern-based units along the former 
border had seized a shipment of 40 anti-aircraft missiles from 
the north. 
  But the GPC spokesman charged that such reports were 
designed 
"to camouflage troop movements (from the south), deceive public 
opinion and divert attention away from the refusal of the YSP to 
sign (an) agreement in Amman this Sunday." 
  The draft agreement was aimed at ending a dispute over the 
administration of the country that has plagued Yemen since last 
August. 
  Despite the political unification of the north and the south 
in May 1990, the armies from the two regions have never merged. 
  The GPC spokesman accused the YSP of "setting new 
conditions, 
revealing its intention of going back" on the accord, which was 
reached January 18. 
  Salih and al-Bid were due to sign the agreement in Amman on 
Sunday, Arab diplomats in the Jordanian capital said Wednesday, 
but Yemeni officials warned it was unlikely the two sides would 
be ready by then. 
  A member of a mediation committee, 'Abdallah al-Jifri, 
predicted that the accord would probably be signed "just before 
Ramadan," the Moslem month of dawn-to-dusk fasting expected to 
start around February 12. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

