<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Signing of Accord Reportedly Postponed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0402100894 Amman AL-RA'Y in Arabic 4 Feb 94 pp 1, 25 </F>
<F P=103> JN0402100894 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-RA'Y </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sanaa, Amman, (News Agencies) -- A responsible 
Jordanian source yesterday said that Yemeni President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih and his deputy 'Ali Salim al-Bid, who had 
informed Jordan of their desire to sign their agreement in Amman 
on Sunday [6 February], have said that they now prefer to carry 
out a disengagement of their forces on the ground before signing 
the agreement. 
  The source said that the two Yemeni leaders, in separate 
telephone contacts with Jordanian officials on 2 February, asked 
for Jordan's help in carrying out this disengagement. 
  The source said that His Majesty King Husayn contacted the 
two Yemeni leaders on the phone last Tuesday, at which time they 
agreed to meet in Amman on Sunday to sign the accord on settling 
the crisis. 
  The General People's Congress [GPC], headed by Yemeni 
President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih has ruled out the possibility of 
an early signing of the national reconciliation agreement to end 
the political crisis, blaming its rival the Yemeni Socialist 
Party [YSP] for this delay. 
  On 2 February, President Salih said that the agreement would 
be signed in the Jordanian capital on Saturday, but Planning 
Minister 'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani, a GPC member, ruled out the 
early signing of the agreement. 
  Al-Iryani told a news conference that no arrangements have 
been made to sign the agreement either in Amman or in Yemen 
since the YSP, under Vice President 'Ali Salim al-Bid, has come 
forth with new conditions. 
  Al-Iryani said that the GPC was preparing to go to Amman on 
Saturday but that information became available indicating that 
new conditions have been set and that he could not now say if 
the GPC would go to Amman on Saturday. 
  Al-Iryani added: The new conditions deal with 
constitutional, security, military, and legal affairs that were 
not mentioned in the agreement that the committee comprising 
representatives from all parties, including the GPC and YSP, 
reached in mid-January. The minister said: This is a new 
interpretation and this is strange and surprising. 
  Al-Iryani did not elaborate further, but political sources 
say that it seems that the YSP is asking for guarantees from the 
security bodies that are run by President Salih's supporters 
concerning the safety of its officials, and insists that the 
agreement be implemented before all of its officials return to 
Sanaa. 
  Al-Iryani said: The GPC has no reservations about the 
contents of the agreement. We are ready to sign everything that 
it contains. The GPC is even ready to sign it on board a vessel 
in high seas. He added: The GPC's stand is that the agreement 
should be signed as soon as possible without any obstacles. 
Those who set new conditions should be held responsible. 
  The YSP yesterday said it seized antiaircraft missiles while 
its northern adversaries were moving them toward the south. 
  This announcement highlights the crisis that threatens Yemen 
with fragmentation and takes place at a time when political 
leaders have ruled out the possibility of an early signing of 
the agreement. 
  A YSP spokesman said that a southern brigade seized an army 
vehicle carrying 40 antiaircraft missiles from the north to the 
south. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

