<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th: 'Arafat-Peres Meeting To Settle Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0402114794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1115 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0402114794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 4 Feb (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, political 
adviser to Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat, has stated that 
the meeting between 'Arafat and Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on 
Peres in Cairo on Monday [7 February] will settle numerous 
issues regarding the document formulated in Davos, Switzerland, 
last week. In a statement to MENA today, Sha'th said the Davos 
document is considered to be an integrated deal, stressing that 
the Palestinian party will not commit itself to implementing its 
obligations in the document unless the Israelis implement the 
articles relating to them. 
  Dr. Sha'th pointed out that the Palestinian-Israeli meetings 
were scheduled to continue in Cairo after the 'Arafat-Peres 
meeting in Davos but the Israeli party suspended them until 
after 'Arafat and Peres meet in Cairo. He noted that the 
Palestinian-Israeli committee meetings are expected to resume in 
Cairo directly after the 'Arafat-Peres meeting in Cairo. 
  Dr. Sha'th highlighted that the Palestinian party can 
perform 
its tasks in running the self-rule administration in the Gaza 
Strip and the Jericho area immediately after the signing of the 
Palestinian-Israeli agreement. 
  MENA has learned that differences occurred between Israeli 
Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin and Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres 
over the Davos document. Palestinian sources told MENA that the 
main dispute within the Israeli leadership focuses mainly on who 
should take the credit for achieving tangible results and 
reaching an agreement with the Palestinian party. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

