<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegates Conclude Negotiations in Washington </TI></H3>
<H4>   PLO, Israel on `Practical' Discussion </H4>
<F P=102> TA0302170794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1600 GMT 3 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0302170794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The 12th round of peace talks in Washington ended 
today. Our correspondent in Washington Arye Golan reports that 
the delegation heads will meet again in approximately two weeks. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher will then leave for a tour 
of the Middle East. 
  In the talks between the Palestinian and Israeli 
delegations, 
it was agreed that the parties would discuss the establishment 
of the Palestinian council, decide on the modalities of the 
elections in the territories, and modify laws in the territories 
prior to the inception of Palestinian self-government. However, 
any practical discussion of these issues would only start after 
an agreement on the implementation of the Gaza-Jericho First 
proposal has been signed. U.S. sources assessed that due to the 
delay in the negotiations on the implementation of the 
Declaration of Principles, the elections for the autonomy 
council would be postponed and would not be held this summer. 
  Some progress on environmental issues was reported in the 
talks between the Jordanian and Israeli delegations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

