<H3> <TI>   Velayati Meets Romanian Counterpart in Bucharest </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302195294 Tehran IRNA in English 1710 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, Feb. 3, IRNA -- Iranian and Romanian 
foreign ministers discussed issues relevant to the security and 
unity of the European countries as well as developments in 
central Asia in their second round of talks here today. 
  A source close to the talks said that Romanian Foreign 
Minister Teodor Viorel Melescanu had raised the issue of 
cooperation between the Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO) 
which grouped Iran and nine neighbours, and the Organization of 
the Black Sea Littoral States. 
  The two decided the issue should be followed up by the 
secretariats of the two organizations, the source added. 
  Iranian Foreign Minister 'Ali Akbar Velayati and his 
Romanian 
counterpart inked two political and trade agreements as well as 
a plan on the scientific, educational, cultural and art 
exchanges at the end of the meeting. 
  Talking to reporters after the meeting, Velayati said the 
agreements reached by the two countries showed that the two were 
keen to further expand their ties. 
  Asked about the attempted assassination against President 
Akbar Hashemi-Rafsanjani last Tuesday, Velayati condemned 
terrorism, and expressed pleasure that the terrorist act had 
failed. 
  He also said that Islamic Iran would spare no efforts in the 
way of the establishment of a just and honorable peace in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

