<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th: Agreement `Closer Than Some Might Think' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0302165294 Jerusalem AL-QUDS in Arabic 3 Feb 94 pp 1, 18 </F>
<F P=103> TA0302165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem AL-QUDS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Salih Abu-Hamad] </F>
  [Text] Gaza -- Dr. Nabil Sha'th, chief Palestinian 
negotiator at the Taba talks, described yesterday the meetings 
in Davos between Palestinian leader Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli 
Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres as being on the level of 
responsibility. He said those meetings produced positive results 
which three months of talks with Israeli negotiators could not 
produce. Sha'th expressed the belief that what was achieved in 
Davos was the most that the Palestinians could achieve. He 
said: Today we are very close, closer than some might think, to 
reaching an agreement ensuring the beginning of implementation 
of the declaration of principles. 
  Sha'th, however, refused to say when he expects a final 
agreement to be signed, adding: Our negotiating experience with 
the Israelis makes it difficult for us to set any timeframe. 
  In an exclusive statement to AL-QUDS, Sha'th said: We should 
always remember that we are in a transitional stage in which the 
Israelis will maintain their presence in two points -- the 
settlements and the borders. It was agreed in the Declaration 
of Principles to call those points "foreign security and the 
settlements' security." We succeeded in confining this presence 
to the narrowest possible geographic area with the provision 
that there will be a Palestinian presence opposite the Israeli 
presence. Sha'th stressed that the Davos accord preserved 
Palestinian personal and national dignity. 
  On whether the prisoners' issue was raised at the 
'Arafat-Peres talks, he said: We are talking about an overall 
agreement that includes a reasonable timetable for releasing all 
Palestinian prisoners, without exception. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

