<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Source:' Kabul Forces Not Accepting Cease-fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302221394 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 2030 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302221394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Fighting has decreased between rival groups in 
Afghanistan. Our correspondent reports from Islamabad. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Kabul was relatively calm today 
with clouds, rain, and snow calming clashes between rival groups. 
  Meanwhile a source close to the government of Borhanoddin 
Rabbani reported attacks by government fighter planes on the 
northern Afghan airport of Jozjan. 
  The source who is close to Rabbani, also emphasized that 
forces supporting the president will not agree to a fresh 
temporary cease-fire in the current fighting. 
  The coordination council in opposition to Rabbani's 
government announced last night that, following a request by the 
UN secretary general's special envoy in Afghan affairs, the 
opposition was ready to accept a four-day cease-fire on the 
condition that negotiations would concentrate on the resignation 
of Rabbani from his post. 
  In reply to this suggestion by the opposition, the source, 
Seyyed Habib Shah Hamed, emphasized that Rabbani will hold the 
presidential post until the end of his term. 
  Meanwhile the Kabul Jihadi commanders and a 100-strong 
mediation group from east Afghanistan, led by Maulawi 
Jallalulddin Haqani, who have spent three days in Kabul, 
continued their negotiations today with the representatives of 
President Rabbani and Prime Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar, and 
tried to prepare and propose a mediating plan that would be 
acceptable to both sides so as to prepare the grounds for 
negotiations and an understanding between the president and the 
prime minister of Afghanistan. 

</TEXT>

