<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Questions Pakistan's Bhutto on UN Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0402083394 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0630 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0402083394 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Jammu and Kashmir, a government spokesman 
questioned the moral right of Pakistan Prime Minister Ms. 
Benazir Bhutto to take up the issue of human rights in Kashmir. 
He said Pakistan sponsored militants are the main violators of 
human rights. He pointed out that since January 1990, these 
militants have killed as many as 2,300 innocent civilians -- 
mostly Kashmiri Muslims -- and abducted more than 1,000 people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-34148 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes024_r_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-024 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Notes Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0402113294 Delhi All India Radio General Overseas Service 
in English 1010 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0402113294 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio General Overseas Service 
in English 1010 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Ashok Sharma] </F>
  [Text] For over four years now, Pakistan has been turning 
all international meetings into a battleground to embarrass 
India, particularly on human rights issue. Constrained somewhat 
by the accepted of not raising bilateral issues at such 
gatherings, Pakistan has taken to raising the Kashmir issue 
under the garb of the alleged human rights violations in the 
valley. In this attempt Pakistan has been encouraged to a great 
extent by the Clinton administration making the human rights 
issue its major policy plank. A view seems to prevail in 
Islamabad that Washington can intercede on its behalf and force 
India to agree to a solution on terms favorable to Pakistan. 
Excelling her predecessor Mr. Nawaz Sharif in anti-India tirade, 
Ms. Benazir Bhutto's private attitude toward India has vitiated 
whatever atmosphere had been generated for good-neighborly ties 
in recent years. 
  Recently, the dispute drowned all hopes at the Human Rights 
Commission meeting at the Geneva with Ms. Bhutto stopping just 
short of calling for an all out war against India. Her aim 
seems to build pressure on the Human Rights Commission of the 
United Nations to pass a resolution against India. She said 
that success of any future talks between Islamabad and New Delhi 
had to be linked to the human rights situation in the Kashmir 
valley. Pakistan's insistence on the implementation of UN 
resolutions on Kashmir belied its intentions. Indian finance 
minister and leader of Indian delegation to the 50th session of 
the UN Human Rights Commission at Geneva, Dr. Manmohan Singh, 
exposed the game plan of Pakistan and said to this date 45 years 
later, Pakistan continues to remain in illegal occupation of 
one-third of Jammu and Kashmir in violation of the UN resolution 
and, therefore, there is no possibility for a plebiscite as a 
precondition of this said UN resolution demands that Pakistan 
will have to withdraw all its forces and tribal population from 
the Pakistan-occupied Kashmir. Accession of Jammu and Kashmir 
to India not only enjoys perfect legal validity, but had also 
been sanctified by a popular will. Seeking the support of the 
world community in its struggle against Pakistan's sponsored 
terrorism in Jammu and Kashmir, Dr. Manmohan Singh said that 
this externally inspired terrorism challenged India's 
territorial integrity and sought to divert its intentions from 
the basic task of nation-building. Lambasting Pakistan for 
misusing the UN forum to launch an uncalled- for tirade against 
India on human rights, he said that an index of India's 
commitment to human rights and the rule of law was the restraint 
shown during the Hazratbal crisis generated by the seizure of 
the holy shrine by Pakistan-supported terrorists. 
  Earlier, replying to Pakistani Prime Minister Ms. Benazir 
Bhutto's harp on human rights in Kashmir, former chief minister 
of jammu and Kashmir, Dr. Farooq Abdullah, termed the propaganda 
as false and malicious and said that it was a well-planned 
attempt on her part to promote terrorism in the state with a 
view to grab it. He also reminded Pakistan of the tragic plight 
of the Ahmediyas, the Sindhis, Shi'ites, Christians and other 
minority communities in that country which is a telling 
commentary on Islamabad's concern for human rights. 
  Human rights in India are well protected. A national 
commission for human rights has been established which is quite 
powerful. Indian legal system also provided sufficient remedial 
framework of punishing human rights violations. Permanent under 
secretary of British Foreign Office, David Gillmore, who is on a 
visit to India has lauded the sensitivity of Indian Government 
toward human rights. He has praised India's continuing and ever 
greater transparency in Kashmir on human rights issue and called 
for strong action by international community against states who 
are guilty of cross border terrorism. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-34149 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes024_r_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-024 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Views Prospects for German Investment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0402062794 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0245 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0402062794 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by A. Karuppaswamy] </F>
  [Text] The Indo-German relations and cooperation in 
industry and scientific development has a new vigor with the 
visit of the prime minister, Mr. Narasimha Rao, to Germany. The 
Germans also take cognizance of the importance of such a visit 
when Germany is renewing its outside endeavor and enagement 
after two and a half years of internal problem of unification. 
Businessmen and industrialists along with the government were 
very busy during the last two years. Inactivities concerned 
with creating parity between the two Germanys radically opposed 
with each in everything except the geographical contiguity 
artificially separated by a manmade wall [sentence as heard]. 
  Germany is now looking for new grounds for investing and 
adequate return for their investment. The economic reforms 
toward globalization of market in India has made Germany 
immensely interested in collaboration. Mr. Narasimha Rao's 
assurance to the German industrialists that India is pressing 
ahead with economic reforms is a reassurance to many of them for 
removing their hesitation to open new units or financing Indian 
projects. The creation of an Asian-Pacific Committee of German 
Industry is a major step toward consolidating Indo-German 
cooperation. The low labor cost and skill of workers and the 
fairly unexploited market in India is the most potential market 
for German industrialists. The meeting between the prime 
minister and the federal minister for economic development and 
the German cochairman of the Indo-German Consultative Group in 
Bonn has paved the way for narrowing down some of the 
constraints. 
  India's largest trading partner and market for Indian export 
in Europe will further invite Indian exports of silk, textiles, 
leather, basic chemicals, precious stones and engineering item. 
On their side, investment in lignite-based power plants, joint 
ventures like power equipment and scientific and institutional 
establishments are some of the added German ventures in India 
contemplated immediately. The German Investment Development 
Company, which has an office in Bombay, is accelerating its 
involvement in speeding up implementing the 2,500 approved 
projects for collaboration. In all, Germany is expected to 
exploit the scheme with the potentials of 75,000 rupees. 
  Politically, the Indo-German relations are always cordial 
and 
consistent with adequate understanding in international fora. 
Germans are well aware of the fact that India was one among the 
first to establish diplomatic relations with Germany after the 
withdrawal of allied forces. The unequivocal stand of Germany 
on developments in Kashmir and its neutrality speaks of its 
noninterference in other country's affairs. Such friendly 
attitude and closer economic ties are bound to reflect in 
Indo-German growth as viable economic powers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

