<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Notified of U.S. Air `Violations' 10-20 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN0202173194 Baghdad Republic of Iraq Radio Network in 
Arabic 1500 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0202173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad Republic of Iraq Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Iraq has protested again over the continued 
violations of its airspace by U.S. aircraft for purposes of 
surveillance, provocation, and dropping of flares. 
  In a letter to UN Secretary General Butrus Ghali, Iraq noted 
that from 10-20 January U.S. aircraft continued to violate Iraqi 
airspace. They carried out 738 air sorties covering large areas 
of northern and southern Iraq. 
  On 11 January, a U.S. TR-1 reconnaissance plane violated 
Iraqi airspace. Afterward, it flew in the direction of Saudi 
airspace. On 3 January [as heard], the same plane violated Iraqi 
airspace. It mainly overflew the al-Basrah, al-Nasiriyah, 
al-'Amarah, southern al-Diwaniyah, and southern al-Najaf areas. 
Afterward, it flew in the direction of Saudi airspace. 
  The letter indicates that on 18 January, two U.S. aircraft 
dropped two flares 10 km south of Alqosh in Ninawa governorate. 
  An enemy air formation dropped a flare south of Alqosh 
hamlet 
in Ninawa governorate. Another formation dropped a flare 10 km 
south of the Alqosh area in Ninawa governorate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

