<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   New `Terrorist' Camps Reportedly Opened in North </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0402101294 Cairo AL-WAFD in Arabic 30 Jan 94 p 9 </F>
<F P=103> NC0402101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-WAFD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Exclusive" report from Shandi in Sudan's northern region] </F>
  [Text] In a new development the Sudanese Government has 
opened new camps for Arab terrorists in al-Hassaniyah south of 
Shandi, a mountainous area with difficult terrain. The 
government dug several wells, reclaimed 5,000 feddans of land, 
and set up a number of farms to ensure provisions for the 
"Yarmuk," "al-Hudaybiyah," and "al-Qadisiyah" camps, where 
Egyptian, Algerian, Tunisian, and Palestinian terrorists will be 
trained in addition to some Asian and African nationals. 
  Dr. Usamah Bin-Ladin, who is wanted by the law in several 
Arab countries, is helping the Sudanese Government to finance 
these camps. Lieutenant General 'Umar al-Bashir issued a decree 
-- which was published by the newspaper AL-INQADH on Wednesday, 
5 January -- granting 1,550 square meters of residential land to 
Bin-Ladin's al- Hijrah Company to build its headquarters on. 
  Al-Bashir's decree also transferred the ownership of "al- 
Mukabarat" agricultural project in the Northern region to 
Bin-Ladin. Agricultural produce from the project's 20,000 
feddans will used to supply the terrorist camps. These camps 
are being opened in the Northern Region in the wake of the 
amendment of the Sudanese Citizenship Law. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

