<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   DUP Rejects Regional Self-Determination Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0402101394 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 2 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM0402101394 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Democratic Unionist Party Rejects </F>
Self-Determination"] 
  [Text] London, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- The opposition 
Sudanese Democratic Unionist Party yesterday announced its 
rejection of the self-determination proposal, saying that the 
problem of the south and any other regional problems can only be 
radically solved within a democratic framework and on an 
amicable basis. 
  In a statement issued from Cairo yesterday the party called 
for safeguarding Sudanese unity -- territory and people -- 
"toppling the [National Islamic] Front's regime," and holding a 
national constitutional conference based on the Sudanese peace 
agreement and the charter of the [opposition] National 
Democratic Grouping. 
  It also stressed that the self-determination question in 
Sudan has been settled since independence in 1956. 
  It pointed out that this issue has two aspects: a legal 
aspect and a political aspect. It listed the documents opposed 
to undermining national unity. It said: We are not listing the 
legal stipulations and evidence to prove that there are no 
regional problems in our country, but because political debates 
must be based on solid legal and realistic foundations, from 
which to proceed toward finding solutions to the new problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

