<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   SLA Concerned Over Possible Israeli Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA3001175494 Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew 30 Jan 94 p 
10 </F>

<F P=103> TA3001175494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by military correspondent Arye Kiesel] </F>
  [Text] The talk about possible Israeli withdrawal from the 
security zone in the framework of the anticipated arrangement 
with Syria has generated great anxiety among members of the SLA 
[South Lebanese Army] upper echelons. 
  The remarks by U.S. elements in Washington to the effect 
that 
the arrangement with Syria will necessitate a phased Israeli 
withdrawal from the security zone to be carried out over several 
years have reached senior SLA officers and caused much concern. 
  In conversations with senior officers at the IDF [Israel 
Defense Forces] Northern Command, SLA Commander Antoine Lahd's 
aides voiced serious anxiety over the possibility of being 
deserted by Israel. An SLA officer has told IDF commanders: "We 
are afraid you will leave us, and we will become a target for 
the Lebanese and the Syrians." 
  Major General Yitzhaq Mordekhay, the Northern Command 
commander, and brigadier General Gabi Ashkenazi, chief of the 
Liaison Unit With Lebanon, apprised their interlocutors of the 
remarks of Yitzhaq Rabin, prime minister and defense minister, 
who said during a tour of Qiryat Shemona three weeks ago that 
Israel will not desert its allies in south Lebanon. The SLA has 
been apprised of the basic conditions for any possible 
arrangement in south Lebanon and of the Israeli demand to 
guarantee the local residents' safety. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

