<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak on Fundamentalism, Middle East Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0302135894 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 1230 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0302135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Husni Mubarak has stressed that economic 
reforms in the coming stage should take into account social 
justice in order to achieve the objective of protecting the 
low-income groups. 
  President Mubarak said that Egyptians are committed to the 
continuation of the economic reform program, even though they 
have suffered from some of its side effects, because they 
realize that today's sacrifices will ensure economic prosperity 
in the future. 
  In a comprehensive interview with the French magazine 
POLITIQUE INTERNATIONALE [INTERNATIONAL POLICY], President 
Mubarak said fundamentalism is a phenomenon that exists in all 
societies and it is wrong to view it as concerning only Islam. 
He added that the real objective of the terrorist groups is to 
seize power and they are using Islam as a cover. 
  The president said: We are capable of resolving the 
terrorism problem and of putting it in its true perspective. 
  He also stressed that the Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of 
Principles is irrevocable because it reflects the feelings of 
the great majority of Palestinians and Israelis even though the 
agreement is not ideal. He added that the UN resolutions are 
the reference point and framework for the peace process and that 
the current negotiations are hard and need both patience and 
time. He stressed that history does not repeat itself. 
  On the current Arab developments, President Mubarak said: No 
one is happy with the Iraqi people's tribulations. We are 
looking forward to the day when it will be over. 

</TEXT>

